Therefore, under Shockley-Read-Hall (SRH) or defect level recombination, direct oxidation of Fe3+ at the photogenerated hole (hvb
                        +) and indirect reduction of hydroxyl radicals (HO

                        ) were prevented the MB degradation. This is also suggested to reason why low removal efficiency was obtained with an increased Fe3O4 weight ratio loading onto anatase TiO2. However, a better photocatalytic activity of Fe3O4/TiO2 nanoparticles was obtained with a decreased Fe3O4 weight ratio loading onto anatase TiO2 leading to an improved charged separation of the photogenerated electron hole-pairs due to the transfer of the photoexcited electron from Fe3O4 nanoparticles to anatase TiO2 is assisted and that led to a better photocatalytic performance. Therefore, the weight ratio of Fe3O4 to TiO2 was kept at 0.125: 1 (FT0.125). These results are similar to a study carried out by Salamat et al. [10].
